Gary Danko, I am relieved you lived up to all the hype I kept hearing about. The 4.5 stars I'm giving you is simply because there was nothing special about the atmosphere of this place, nor the service (there wasn't anything bad to say about it... just nothing to rave about). People were very loud and chatty, and though I loved how my BF and I were caught up in a Facebook-posting, Yelp-picture taking frenzy with two other couples we were sitting in between, I didn't really care for the lack of space in here - elbows to elbows literally. Right as we were seated, we were each handed an amuse bouche of a small minty falafel ball, which was delicious in cleansing our palate. Appetizers: - Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar: I did a double take and almost mistook these for baby clams because they were THAT small. Never had caviar before but man, it was goooood. I was under the wrong impression that caviar was salty and fishy (much like my first experience with sea urchin) but was pleasantly surprised that this one added just the right amount of saltiness without the fishiness to the oysters. - Lobster risotto: EXCELLENT! I NEVER order risotto due to bad past experiences with it but this plate was worth it. Portion was a bit much for an appetizer but the lobster pieces were buttery, while the asparagus and peas gave it a nice crunchy texture to the perfectly cooked risotto (no pebbly rice!). Main: - Seared sea scallops, Lobster tail: both made my eyes roll back and say "Mmmm..." - Quail stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms & Quinoa: the quinoa gave it an oddly interesting and refreshing taste (much like the minty falafel ball did); it was like a more-welcomed couscous for me, probably because it was soaked in all the fatty foie gras goodness. The quail meat itself could have been cooked and presented better - it was a little on the drier side and not very tender. - Seared Filet of Beef: juicy, tender, melt-in-your-mouth-just-the-way-you-like it good. Dessert: - Lemon souffle cake with Creme Fraiche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet: pass on the souffle cake (just weird with the mix of cheesy and lemon-y flavors that wasn't in a cheesecake form, just soft spongy cake). Sorbet was very tart if you like it that way. -French Macaron Ice Cream Sandwiches: Lemon, Rhubarb, Coffee. The rhubarb was flavorless. Coffee was like drinking a strong shot of espresso, which my BF loved. I preferred the tart lemon instead. Overall, really good! For the wonderful food we were served, I definitely cannot wait to have another reason to come back again... Gary Danko is definitely in a close running for the best high-end restaurant on my list.

No. Frankly, when the slightest hint of hunger is felt in a Samoan, they have a unique gift whereby the brain becomes completely detached from the body. Looking forward to having dinner @ Gary Danko, I came in with high expectations. They met them with the service, but the food was a hit or miss without any consistency. Our night started with a staring match with the valet guys to see who which one of the two would come out to the street and take our car. Finally one got the hint and on we went to dinner. Our table wasn't ready so we waited at the bar and had a cocktail. Twenty five minutes later, our table was set for us. They brought out a yellow heirloom tomato gazpacho soup with crab meat as a peace offering. The soup had a sweetness to it and the crab meat just added another dimension of flavor to it. Amuse Bouche: Buckwheat blini with smoked salmon and caviar. The best blini ive ever had, light, airy, crisp, smoky buttery flavors from the salmon and salty pop in your mouth layer from the caviar. We did the four course dinner. Appetizer: Glazed oysters with osetra caviar, zucchini pearls, lettuce cream. The oysters were tender, firm, with a fresh clean taste from the zucchini pearls, lettuce cream, and accented by the saltiness of the caviar. Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms, and lemon soy dressing: The wifey had this dish, but i finished it and slurped up the lemon soy dressing. The seared tuna was extremely tender and melted in my mouth. It tasted like eating fresh sashimi. The avocado added a clean creamy fat flavor and the enoki mushrooms added the meaty texture. 1st course: Risotto with crab, rock shrimp, corn, peas, and roasted tomatoes. The risotto was creamy but a little firm. There was very little crab or shrimp in the dish. The peas were firm with a small crunch to offset the risotto texture. Now, i wasn't too happy with the amount of tomato puree on top of the dish. I think it killed the other subtle flavors in the dish. Mushroom dusted sea scallops with english peas puree, shimeji mushrooms and meyer lemon. Two huge seared tender scallops with a sweet pea puree and sweet but tart meyer lemon sauce. I would call this a nice ceviche. Main course: Quail stuffed with foie gras, mushrooms, quinoa, fregola, and black olive pine nut gremolata. I was disappointed with this dish. My quail was a bit dry and there was no flavor of the foie gras at all. The mushrooms were tender with the quinoa adding a light nutty flavor. Herb crusted loin of lamb with tian of vegetables and polenta. Another dish that lacked flavor. The lamb was cooked perfectly but tasted bland. The tagine of zucchini and tomatoes added no additional flavors or dimension and the same with the polenta. Dessert: Trio of crème brulée (chocolate, butterscotch, traditional) with assorted cookies. The sugar was torched perfectly and all three were rich and creamy. I wasn't too crazy for the cookies with one being a pistachio biscotti. Warm louisiana butter cake. I liked this dish and loved the sweet caramelized peaches along the dark fruit flavors of the huckleberry compote. The service was top notch throughout our dinner. I do have a small beef with the wine prices. I don't mind paying for a good meal and a good bottle of wine, but to charge 3x as much as retail for a bottle? There are certain things that i will balk at and this was one of them. We ended up bringing our own wine and just paid the $35 corkage.

This place was everything that I expected it to be and more. We had a chair and booth type table, and right before I could slide into my side of the booth, the host moved the table aside so that I wouldn't have to slide in. They even have their own purse hangers for women at the table so your purse wouldn't be in the way. I love that none of the waiters or host ever seemed snuck up even if this is one of those places that you would think that they were. All the food that I had is worth coming back for. Go for their seafood dishes, because those seemed to be the most memorable for me. Their desserts were on point also, we had a table of desserts because for one, it was my birthday so we had a little cake for that, we also had the 2 that we ordered (macaron ice cream sandwiches and their souffle), and then they also gave us petit fours. They even send the girls off with a morning after muffin to take home. Yes, it is a pricey place, but for the service, quality of food and if you're a foodie, I think its worth it for at least a special occasion. I definitely want to find another reason to save up some money and come back for another awesome meal here.

That man knows how roast a pig and play some good ol' touchy, touch football.

My nephew Dwayne has a vocal recital across town at Our Lady the Triumphant church and school. Dwayne has an angelic voice and abandonment issues and if he sees my seat empty he is GOING TO LOSE IT and potentially wet himself on stage. I get into my 2006 Chevy Impala, throw Dwayne's car seat out the window, and book it. I GOTTA SEE MY BOY PERFORM. I'm racing 70 miles per hour down San Mildred avenue, weaving in and out of cars, when I hear a pop. Not the good type of pop like when your significant other pops open a can of pringles during your shared bath, a bad pop. My tires out, and there's no way I'm going to make it to hear that sweet boy sing his hymns. It's then that Gary Danko pulls by in his Big Toe truck. Gary toes me to the church and even sticks around to watch Dwayne give angels wings with his beautiful voice. At the end of the show Gary gave Dwayne some advice that I will never for get: he said "Dwayne, you're going to sore higher than any boys ever sored. Touch the sky, my sweet prince, and never let the trollz bring you down".

    Things we ate:

    -Lobster Salad with Avocado, Citrus, Shaved Fennel with Meyer Lemon-Tarragon Vinaigrette
    -Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Rhubarb
    -Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Edamame and Tarragon
    Maple Glaze
    -Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Curried Cauliflower, Cumin-Cilantro Butter and Tamarind Glaze
    -A Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside

    Let me start by saying I love lobster... So you can't go wrong with anything lobster unless you overcook it. lol. So anywho, I did think the salad was a bit bland for my liking but definitely got my greens in. The foie gras was melt in your mouth amazingness. Thanks to one of the other reviewers I saw in quick tips that recommended it. The combo of rhubarb and the other sauce was perfect. Onto the entrees... I had the lobster with potato puree before and it still was amazing! The seared filet of beef was perfectly seasoned and very tasty. Our selection of cheeses, we chose all 5 creamy front row cheeses. Very generous portions and great. You'll definitely have to request more raisin bread though since it was not enough.

    We sat at the bar and the bartender was amazing and very rosy personality. He's also quite knowledgeable about everything in that menu so definitely would recommend him.

    3/28/2010Previous review

    So note to anyone that doesn't have an RSVP or want to wait 2 months to get in, sit at the bar and you'll be served! The main bartender/waiter is amazing and knows his stuff. If you need a well educated waiter, he's the guy! He gave awesome descriptions ranging down to the millions of cheeses they have. They have smaller and bigger hot portions of what we ordered. We ordered all large portions.

    We ordered:
    - Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Salsify and Lettuce Cream
    - Lobster and Fennel Bisque with Dungeness Crab, Peppers and Saffron-Orange Rémoulade
    -Seared Sea Scallops with Butternut Squash Purée, Roasted Apples, Shallots and Red Pepper
    -Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon
    -A Selection of Farmhouse and Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside
    -Trio of Crme Brlée with Assorted Cookies

    So lets starts with the oysters, meh...they were okay...nothing spectacular. The baked at Hog Island Oyster House were way better. The lobster bisque was yummy but I think there was way too much fennel in it. The scallop was succulent and melt in your mouth amazing. Was flavorful and definitely not dry. The lobster was my fave! You can never go wrong with Main lobster!! The cheeses that I don't remember which ones we picked were the creamy ones and yummy! The trio of creme brulee were definitely awesome! There was original, buttercream, and pumpkin. The original and buttercream were my favorite. They also give you an extra treat to take home for breakfast.

    Our bill was $170 which included to cocktails. So quite affordable for a place with spectacular service and fine dining. We didn't even do the 3-5 course set pricing. So I highly recommend and will be back again!

    6/19/2012

    1 check-in

    Gary Danko, I am relieved you lived up to all the hype I kept hearing about. The 4.5 stars I'm giving you is simply because there was nothing special about the atmosphere of this place, nor the service (there wasn't anything bad to say about it... just nothing to rave about). People were very loud and chatty, and though I loved how my BF and I were caught up in a Facebook-posting, Yelp-picture taking frenzy with two other couples we were sitting in between, I didn't really care for the lack of space in here - elbows to elbows literally.

    Right as we were seated, we were each handed an amuse bouche of a small minty falafel ball, which was delicious in cleansing our palate.

    Appetizers:
    - Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar: I did a double take and almost mistook these for baby clams because they were THAT small. Never had caviar before but man, it was goooood. I was under the wrong impression that caviar was salty and fishy (much like my first experience with sea urchin) but was pleasantly surprised that this one added just the right amount of saltiness without the fishiness to the oysters.

    - Lobster risotto: EXCELLENT! I NEVER order risotto due to bad past experiences with it but this plate was worth it. Portion was a bit much for an appetizer but the lobster pieces were buttery, while the asparagus and peas gave it a nice crunchy texture to the perfectly cooked risotto (no pebbly rice!).

    Main:
    - Seared sea scallops, Lobster tail: both made my eyes roll back and say "Mmmm..."

    - Quail stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms & Quinoa: the quinoa gave it an oddly interesting and refreshing taste (much like the minty falafel ball did); it was like a more-welcomed couscous for me, probably because it was soaked in all the fatty foie gras goodness. The quail meat itself could have been cooked and presented better - it was a little on the drier side and not very tender.

    - Seared Filet of Beef: juicy, tender, melt-in-your-mouth-just-the-way-you-like it good.

    Dessert:
    - Lemon souffle cake with Creme Fraiche Panna Cotta and Raspberry Sorbet: pass on the souffle cake (just weird with the mix of cheesy and lemon-y flavors that wasn't in a cheesecake form, just soft spongy cake). Sorbet was very tart if you like it that way.

    -French Macaron Ice Cream Sandwiches: Lemon, Rhubarb, Coffee. The rhubarb was flavorless. Coffee was like drinking a strong shot of espresso, which my BF loved. I preferred the tart lemon instead. Overall, really good!

    For the wonderful food we were served, I definitely cannot wait to have another reason to come back again... Gary Danko is definitely in a close running for the best high-end restaurant on my list.

    "And when I let go of that dietary handcuff, I always rediscover segments of my life when calories and fats were insignificant..."

    What dork walks into a 5 star restaurant off the street wearing a sweatshirt that says "Hanalei Canoe Club" across the back, then sits at the bar and downs food like it was a Shakey's buffet? Oh. Sorry Gary Danko's. That was me.

    O.K. I'd better defend myself and backup a bit. I was attending the Eye for Travel social media conference down the street at the Hyatt in Fisherman's Wharf.  There we all sat like peacocks, strutting our fully connected social selves, Tweetdecked and 4-Squaring away while hanging on to the words of big cheeses from Facebook and Virgin Air. It was ugly. Haha. None other  than Yelp's own COO Geoff Donaker was also in the house, smugly chatting about tactics and customer conversions. And no, he didn't yell, "Hey, is that the Hungry Hawaiian I see in the 2nd row?!"  Hmm. I'm sure he saw me. Maybe he's racist.  Whatever. Frankly, after all the feather fluffing, I was mentally overloaded and ready for food that wasn't the tourist fish & chip fare.  So, what does any good Yelper do? Yelp search.

    Now, keep in mind that my mind was fuzzy, so at that moment, Yelp was akin to a Playboy. I was only looking at the pictures. Woohoo! Gary Danko's was smokin'! Did I pay attention to the notes on attire? No. Did I check out the price range? No. Did I even care about either? No.  Frankly, when the slightest hint of hunger is felt in a Samoan, they have a unique gift whereby the brain becomes completely detached from the body.  Think of those old cartoons with a hypnotized guy shuffling his feet, eyes spiraling, arms outstretched as he makes his way to some comic ending.  

    And there I shuffled into Gary Danko's. I pushed open a pair of non-descript doors to a room that was exploding with laughter and the scent of great food and wines. I froze and was suddenly acutely aware that I was a) the only person wearing a sweatshirt and jeans, b) in a place that was at my budget pain threshold for a supposed quick meal.  Alone. Whatever. I pretended as if I wasn't self-conscious, sat at the bar, and proceeded to order an iced tea. The non-alcoholic kind. The kind that bartenders squint at you as if you had made a comment about their mother.  Whatever. My body was still in the conference networking mode, so I started to chatter with people around me. To my left were two girlfriends who were celebrating a birthday and friendship. Jen and Akiko. I joined too. They happily let me. But the food.

    The beet salad was bursting with full flavors; rich and subtle flavors that can only come from ripe ingredients. My main was the Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Brussels Sprouts, Bacon, Parsnip Purée and Maple Cider.  Wow. I personally like slightly less marbled meat, but I went with it and really focused on enjoying that taboo melt-in-your-mouth marbling.  And when I let go of that dietary handcuff, I always rediscover segments of my life when calories and fats were insignificant.  That time when you're young enough to get away with food murder, but not yet old enough to fully appreciate the decadence. I did. I followed the main with one of their signature cheese platters.  The cheese cart is nice, you choose four, but I've had far grander fare. Either way, order it. You won't be sad.

    All of this ended with sharing Jen's happy birthday treat and a platter full of assorted dessert goodies. Ahhh. Hugs and emails from new friends...and as I departed from that voyage, tapping a tweet on my Blackberry,  I'd have to say. Was all that just a weird dream?

    Our first dinner in SF was at Gary Danko and it was the perfect way to start our trip! It is literally two blocks from the Argonaut Hotel and from the outside, it is very unassuming.  Once you walk in, it's a beautiful and elegant yet cozy restaurant.  

    I opted for a four course tasting while my fiance/husband got the summer tasting menu.  Every course was wonderful - I still think about the summer truffles (sigh).  

    Some highlights:  
    *Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée and Pancetta
    *Seared Filet of Beef with Potatoes Panadera, Swiss Chard, Cassis Glazed Shallots and Bordelaise Butter

    Awesome cheese course as well with over fifteen cheeses to choose from.

    Service was wonderful and the sommelier helped us choose several wines that paired perfectly.  The wine selection is massive as well and because of tasting choices, it was great that we could get several half bottles instead of just a glass or a full bottle.

    Our dinner was on the early side (6:15) and by the time we left, the place was packed.  We're so happy we dined here - coming from Boston and speaking to random people about our trip, everyone recommended Gary Danko. We're happy we came!  It was one of our more expensive meals, but worth it.

    6/17/2010

    What is there to say about Gary Danko that hasn't already been said 2000+ times? Gary Danko is truly fantastic! It's been my number one place to go to since I started yelping back in 2008 and I finally got to go last night and it did not disappoint at all!  As a matter of fact, it surpassed my expectations.

    I love how Gary Danko offers you to customize your courses anyway you want. You can choose something from appetizers, entrees, and dessert, or you can even go for all entrees. The BF and I went for five courses each.

    The chef provided us with complimentary cauliflower soup. I have never had cauliflower soup before but it was delicious! Warm and creamy, it was a great opener.

    Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing - It was very lemony, but I loved the tuna with avocado and mushrooms. The tuna just melts in  your mouth!

    Dungeness Crab Salad with Avocado Mousse, Pineapple, Hearts of Palm and Curry-Lemon Vinaigrette - These perfectly peeled  crab legs were plump and absolutely delicious with the avocado mousse

    Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Morel Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon - Succulent lobster tail and claw.  I loved the potato puree with the edamame beans

    Coconut Thai Curry with Lemongrass, Calamari, Lobster, Scallions and Shiitake Mushrooms - I'm pretty sure the dish I had last night had scallop and oysters in it too... but regardless, I'm not a big coconut curry fan but this dish was really good too! Everything was soo tender and full of flavor from the curry

    Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers and Mustard Sauce - The salmon was cooked nicely, slightly pink in the inside and not dry at all.  It was good, but didn't stand out as much as the other dishes.  I also expected the horseradish to be a little more pungent.

    Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp Purée, Fava Beans, Artichokes and Maple Glaze - I loveddd the roasted pork belly. Sooo tender and it was sooo delicious with the potato-ramp puree.  The tenderloin was tender as well, but I'm not a fan of meat accompanied by sweet sauces.

    Braised Lamb Shoulder and Herb Crusted Loin with Barley Stew, Red Pepper Relish and Cumin Yogurt - Both good but I liked the braised lamb shoulder better.  Braised meats are always more tender.

    Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Carrot-Ginger Purée and Vanilla Poached Rhubarb - So good! The breast was so succulent and well flavored and it was the first time I ever had duck hash.  

    Quail Stuffed with Mushrooms and Quinoa, Artichokes, Olives and Scallion-Potato Cake - Probably one of my favorite dishes.  I've only had quail at Chinese restaurants and they were always fried and dried.  This quail was tender and juicy and boneless.  I loved the lemony flavor of it with all the stuffing.  I'm a big fan of potatoes and I loved the potato cake with the juicy meat.

    Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Caramelized Apricots, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream - Thank you Suzanne for recommending this dessert! I loved it! And I normally don't have a sweet tooth either. The buttercake was rich and moist and went very well with the cold vanilla ice cream.

    We were celebrating the BF's birthday so I was just hoping that the chef could write "happy birthday" on the dessert we ordered.  But one of the staff told me that after all our courses came out, they will bring out a separate cake with a candle and everything. Thank you Gary Danko for the little birthday cake!

    We were also given a little tray of what I only know to call it "mini cookies and treats" and Suzanne gave me a blueberry muffin package to go and said it was from the chef to the ladies.  I had it for breakfast today, it was moist and delicious! I love blueberries!

    The service here was great! The very attentive staff was constantly filling up your water glass, placing bread on our bread dish, folding our napkins whenever we leave the table, and provide us with new utensils for each upcoming course.  

    Gary Danko provided me with a very initimate and beautiful restaurant, absolutely delicious food, and impeccable service.  Thank you for a wonderful dining experience! "Have a good night and hope to see you soon" I DO hope to come back here soon!

    I had friends flew in from Austin and I suggested Gary Danko due to the fact that these friends are iconic yuppies.  Friends from thousands miles away arrived early to our Friday 5:30pm dinner reservation (thanks to Gary Danko's popularity and yelputation); I, on the other hand, traveled from south bay, managed to make it only a mere 45 minutes late.  Of course, while I was "fashionably late", my friends fashionably drank and finished a bottle without me... Regardless, I do appreciate Gary Danko's courtesy of sitting us despite my awful tardiness.

    We all ordered their 3-course menu. Most of my friends went for the wine pairing. I got what I knew I would enjoy - Clos Saint Jean - Chateauneuf-du-Pape.  Absolutely delicious with layers and layers of complexity.

    The amuse bouche - Tomato and Zucchini Soup with Cumin Yoghurt came unexpectedly, with repeated instructions to eat while still warm. Not sure if it was due to my fashionably lateness, I was reprimanded for being late in eating the soup, too :)  

    My first course was Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Peas, Corn and Roasted Tomatoes.  I am not going to pass my judgement on this just because I am biased with anything Risotto.  I rave about the Risotto in a box sold at Trader Joe's and thought it tastes heavenly... so go figure...

    I picked Moroccan Spiced Squab with Raisins, Almonds, Chermoula and Orange-Cumin Carrots as my second course since I have never had it before.  And NO, i don't have the tendency of being animal cruelty.  Squab has texture similar to Quail with a more subtle flavor... Not a fan of Squab itself, but a trooper of fulfilled curiosity.

    As for dessert, we all wanted their famous cheese cart, but none of us had the slightest clue as for what to select.  Staff was accommodating enough to offer us a shared platter of their entire cheese selection.  Life saver!

    Overall experience at Gary Danko is very much pleasant enjoyable.  Great food with impeccable staff/service. Highly recommend!

    Big fan of this restaurant.  Great service, great atmosphere, they've got a bar to kill some time if you're there early.

    Before we started our meal, we got a delicious amuse bouche, and a complimentary salmon caviar blini from the chef.  What a great way to start the meal.  I'm happier than a fat boy in a candy store.

    We started off with the caviar and it came out with some amazing blinis.  I was told even the Chef loves it enough not to swap it out.  This was my 2nd time trying real caviar (first was the French Laundry) and yeah, I could come back just for this dish alone.  I think I might know what coke addicts go through when they suffer withdrawal.

    As for the rest of the food, really good shit came out.  I brought my own bottle of wine (El Molino Pinot Noir, one of the BEST I've ever had, google it, I dare you to be disappointed) and I had the wine pairing...friend: "Mike, who brings a bottle of wine and gets a wine pairing?!"

    yeah, that wasn't one of the best choices I've made.  I can't really remember the dishes, I was pretty toasted.  HOWEVER, I do remember the lobster risotto being pretty good but slightly overcooked on the rice :(  What gives Gary?!  Think I can't recognize an overcooked risotto when I'm plastered?!

    Stuffed Quail was pretty delicious, it was kind of soft despite looking roasted.  We just had quail @ the french laundry so it was kind of disappointing in the sense that you have mr. 3 star thomas keller serving the most perfectly roasted quail that's pink in the middle and then Gary's, which was still tasty, just you know, it'd be like eating a gourmet burger and then having a big mac the next day, it's got no chance.

    The service was awesome.  My friend and I stayed for an hour or two extra just playing poker at the table until like midnight and the staff didn't complain at all.  Totally would've understood if they told us to get the fuck out.

    I'm definitely going back...and I'll see how late I can play poker before they shove me out the door.

    I heard of Gary Danko for almost three years since I moved to San Francisco but never got a chance to visit until last Friday. We changed our reservation three weeks before our original reservation date so we got a 10pm time slot.
    The outside of the restaurant is not quite obvious since I realized I have passed by Gary Danko on cable car but never noticed it.
    We were greeted when we entered the restaurant at around 9:58pm and got a seat at the bar to wait for our table to be ready.
    I really like the way they give people to choose their own courses from the menu without any limitaion. You can get one appetizer, one main course, and one desserts, but you can also get four desserts or five main courses if you want to.
    All the courses was great except the dessert. I ordered the Strawberry Soufflé with Strawberry Sauce and Strawberry Sorbet. I personally think it was too sweet with the strawberry and cream sauce the server added in front of me.
    Will come back next time but might skip the dessert and get one more main course instead.

    8/21/2009

    10 photos

    Looking forward to having dinner @ Gary Danko, I came in with high expectations. They met them with the service, but the food was a hit or miss without any consistency.

    Our night started with a staring match with the valet guys to see who which one of the two would come out to the street and take our car. Finally one got the hint and on we went to dinner. Our table wasn't ready so we waited at the bar and had a cocktail. Twenty five minutes later, our table was set for us.

    They brought out a yellow heirloom tomato gazpacho soup with crab meat as a peace offering. The soup had a sweetness to it and the crab meat just added another dimension of flavor to it.

    Amuse Bouche:
    Buckwheat blini with smoked salmon and caviar. The best blini ive ever had, light, airy, crisp, smoky buttery flavors from the salmon and salty pop in your mouth layer from the caviar. We did the four course dinner.

    Appetizer:
    Glazed oysters with osetra caviar, zucchini pearls, lettuce cream. The oysters were tender, firm, with a fresh clean taste from the zucchini pearls, lettuce cream, and accented by the saltiness of the caviar.

    Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki  mushrooms, and lemon soy dressing: The wifey had this dish, but i finished it and slurped up the lemon soy dressing. The seared tuna was extremely tender and melted in my mouth. It tasted like eating fresh sashimi. The avocado added a clean creamy fat flavor and the enoki mushrooms added the meaty texture.

    1st course:
    Risotto with crab, rock shrimp, corn, peas, and roasted tomatoes. The risotto was creamy but a little firm. There was very little crab or shrimp in the dish. The peas were firm with a small crunch to offset the risotto texture. Now, i wasn't too happy with the amount of tomato puree on top of the dish. I think it killed the other subtle flavors in the dish.

    Mushroom dusted sea scallops with english peas puree, shimeji mushrooms and meyer lemon. Two huge seared tender scallops with a sweet pea puree and sweet but tart meyer lemon sauce. I would call this a nice ceviche.

    Main course:
    Quail stuffed with foie gras, mushrooms, quinoa, fregola, and black olive pine nut gremolata. I was disappointed with this dish. My quail was a bit dry and there was no flavor of the foie gras at all. The mushrooms were tender with the quinoa adding a light nutty flavor.

    Herb crusted loin of lamb  with tian of vegetables and polenta. Another dish that lacked flavor. The lamb was cooked perfectly  but tasted bland. The tagine of zucchini and tomatoes added no additional flavors or dimension and the same with the polenta.

    Dessert:
    Trio of crème brulée (chocolate, butterscotch, traditional) with assorted cookies. The sugar was torched perfectly and all three were rich and creamy. I wasn't too crazy for the cookies with one being a pistachio biscotti.

    Warm louisiana butter cake. I liked this dish and loved the sweet caramelized peaches along the dark fruit flavors of the huckleberry compote.

    The service was top notch throughout our dinner. I do have a small beef with the wine prices. I don't mind paying for a good meal and a good bottle of wine, but to charge 3x as much as retail for a bottle? There are certain things that i will balk at and this was one of them. We ended up bringing our own wine and just paid the $35 corkage.

    This place was everything that I expected it to be and more. We had a chair and booth type table, and right before I could slide into my side of the booth, the host moved the table aside so that I wouldn't have to slide in. They even have their own purse hangers for women at the table so your purse wouldn't be in the way. I love that none of the waiters or host ever seemed snuck up even if this is one of those places that you would think that they were. All the food that I had is worth coming back for. I had the lobster risotto, foie gras (I came here before the ban), and the lobster dish with the potato puree and the boyfriend got a lot of the meat dishes. Go for their seafood dishes, because those seemed to be the most memorable for me. Their desserts were on point also, we had a table of desserts because for one, it was my birthday so we had a little cake for that, we also had the 2 that we ordered (macaron ice cream sandwiches and their souffle), and then they also gave us petit fours. They even send the girls off with a morning after muffin to take home.

    Yes, it is a pricey place, but for the service, quality of  food and if you're a foodie, I think its worth it for at least a special occasion. I definitely want to find another reason to save up some money and come back for another awesome meal here.
